Welcome Michael Williams,

there is a very well established method in maven to do that properly.

You need 4 `pom.xml`:

```
project/pom.xml
project/backend/pom.xml
project/frontend/pom.xml
project/db/pom.xml
```
The first `project/pom.xml` may contain this `xml`:



    &lt;project&gt; ...
      &lt;packaging&gt;pom&lt;/packaging&gt;
      &lt;modules&gt;
        &lt;module&gt;backend&lt;/module&gt;
        &lt;module&gt;frontend&lt;/module&gt;
        &lt;module&gt;db&lt;/module&gt;
      &lt;/modules&gt;
    &lt;/project&gt;

Would you concider this as an approach?

If you are trying out Kotlin Multiplatform, specifically for JVM and web development, replacing this:

    jvm {
            jvmToolchain(8)
            withJava()
            testRuns[&quot;test&quot;].executionTask.configure {
                useJUnitPlatform()
